## Entities and Value Objects

### Entity — has identity, is mutable
An entity's identity persists even as its attributes change. Two entities with the same attributes are NOT equal if their IDs differ.

```java
@Entity
public class Order {
    private OrderId id;        // identity
    private CustomerId customerId;
    private List<OrderLine> lines;
    private Money total;
    private OrderStatus status;

    // Two orders with same lines but different IDs are different orders
    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        return this.id.equals(((Order) o).id); // identity-based equality
    }
}
```

### Value Object — no identity, immutable
Defined by its attributes. Two value objects with same attributes ARE equal.

```java
public record Money(BigDecimal amount, Currency currency) {
    public Money add(Money other) {
        if (!this.currency.equals(other.currency))
            throw new DomainException("Currency mismatch");
        return new Money(this.amount.add(other.amount), this.currency);
    }
    // Records are immutable — good Value Object
}

// Two Money objects with same amount and currency are equal
new Money(100, USD).equals(new Money(100, USD)); // true
```

## Aggregates

An aggregate is a **cluster of related objects treated as a unit** for data changes. It has an **Aggregate Root** — the only entry point for modifications.

### Rules:
1. External code can only reference the **Aggregate Root**, not internal entities
2. All invariants (business rules) within an aggregate must always be consistent
3. Only one aggregate root is modified per transaction
4. References to other aggregates by ID only (not object reference)

```java
public class Order { // Aggregate Root
    private OrderId id;
    private List<OrderLine> lines = new ArrayList<>(); // internal entity
    private OrderStatus status;

    public void addLine(ProductId productId, Quantity qty, Money price) {
        // Business invariant: cannot add to confirmed order
        if (status != DRAFT) throw new DomainException("Order already confirmed");
        lines.add(new OrderLine(productId, qty, price));
    }

    public void confirm() {
        if (lines.isEmpty()) throw new DomainException("Cannot confirm empty order");
        this.status = CONFIRMED;
        // domain event raised
        registerEvent(new OrderConfirmedEvent(this.id));
    }
    // OrderLine cannot be accessed/modified except through Order
}
```

## Domain Events

Domain events represent **something significant that happened** in the domain — they're facts, named in past tense.

```java
// Domain event
public record OrderConfirmedEvent(
    OrderId orderId,
    CustomerId customerId,
    Money total,
    Instant occurredAt
) implements DomainEvent {}

// Published from aggregate after business operation
public class Order {
    private List<DomainEvent> events = new ArrayList<>();

    public void confirm() {
        // business logic...
        events.add(new OrderConfirmedEvent(id, customerId, calculateTotal(), Instant.now()));
    }

    public List<DomainEvent> releaseEvents() {
        var released = new ArrayList<>(events);
        events.clear();
        return released;
    }
}

// Application service publishes after saving aggregate
@Transactional
public void confirmOrder(OrderId orderId) {
    Order order = orderRepository.findById(orderId);
    order.confirm();
    orderRepository.save(order);
    eventPublisher.publishAll(order.releaseEvents()); // publish after commit
}
```
